(216, 1, '2024-12-19 19:02:08', '2024-12-19 19:02:08', 'The RFID (Radio Frequency Identification) module for Arduino is a popular component used for creating identification and access control systems. It allows the Arduino to communicate with RFID tags or cards through radio waves, enabling the reading of stored data from these tags. The module consists of an RFID reader and an antenna, which work together to detect and read RFID tags within a certain range. This technology is commonly used in applications like smart locks, inventory management, and security systems. By interfacing with an Arduino, the RFID module can be programmed to perform specific actions when a valid tag is detected, such as unlocking doors or logging entry times.\n\nKey Features:\nOperating Frequency: Typically 13.56 MHz, suitable for most RFID applications.\nCommunication Protocol: Usually communicates via UART (serial) or SPI for easy connection with Arduino boards.\nRange: Detection range varies from 3 cm to 10 cm, depending on the type of RFID tag and the module\'s power.\nCompatibility: Compatible with standard RFID tags and cards (e.g., Mifare).\nPower Supply: Typically operates at 5V, compatible with Arduino.\nEasy Integration: Comes with libraries and examples to facilitate quick setup and programming with Arduino.\nApplications: Access control systems, asset tracking, smart card systems, and more.\nThe RFID module for Arduino provides a convenient and reliable solution for creating wireless identification systems, offering seamless integration and security features for a variety of projects.', 'RFID Module', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '111-autosave-v1', '', '', '2024-12-19 19:02:08', '2024-12-19 19:02:08', '', 111, 'http://localhost/?p=216', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(217, 1, '2024-12-19 19:08:52', '2024-12-19 19:08:52', 'Quickly and easily get started with learning electronics using the Arduino Starter Kit, which have a universal appeal to STEM fans at home, businesses in STEAM industries, and schools alike. No prior experience is required, as the kits introduce both coding and electronics through fun, engaging, and hands-on projects. You can use the starter kit to teach students about current, voltage, and digital logic as well as the fundamentals of programming. There’s an introduction to sensors and actuators and how to understand both digital and analog signals. Within all this, you’ll be teaching students how to think critically, learn collaboratively, and solve problems.\n', 'Starter Kit for Arduino', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '107-autosave-v1', '', '', '2024-12-19 19:08:52', '2024-12-19 19:08:52', '', 107, 'http://localhost/?p=217', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
